---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import {
  NORTH_STAR,
  OPERATING_QUESTION,
  VERDICT,
  ASYMMETRY,
  PROBES,
  V02_PROBES,
} from '../../data/frame-construction';
import { REGISTERED_FUTURES } from '../../data/registered-futures';
import { VERDICT_PROTOCOL } from '../../data/verdict-protocol';
import { CAPABILITY_LADDER, VERDICT_RELEVANT_FROM } from '../../data/capability-ladder';
import runBundles from '../../data/run-bundles.json';

const graded = runBundles.filter((b) => b.status === 'graded');
const live = runBundles.filter((b) => b.status === 'registered-sealed');
---

<Base
  title="The Test — pathtoAGI"
  description="The operating question, operationalized: sealed synthetic worlds with a contamination floor of zero by construction, deterministic mechanical grading, and a deliberate scoring asymmetry. The historical probe suites are preserved as retired artifacts."
>
  <section class="max-w-3xl">
    <p class="eyebrow">The test · frame construction under seal</p>
    <h1 class="display mt-4 text-4xl sm:text-5xl">The Test</h1>
    <p class="lede mt-6">{OPERATING_QUESTION}</p>
    <p class="prose mt-6">
      The distinctive thing this record asks is whether a system can perform
      <strong>frame construction</strong>: notice that the inherited ontology
      is wrong, find the representation no prompt handed it, and derive
      consequences that survive contact with reality. The test is a growing
      suite of <strong>sealed synthetic worlds</strong> — laws generated after
      commitment, so they never existed in any training corpus; attempts
      anchored before reveals; grading deterministic against the sealed truth
      and reproducible bit-for-bit by anyone.
    </p>
    <div class="surface-quiet mt-6 p-5" style="border-radius: 10px;">
      <p class="eyebrow">The north star · declared beyond this instrument's own scope</p>
      <p class="serif mt-2 text-lg" style="color: var(--color-ink);">{NORTH_STAR.question}</p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{NORTH_STAR.status}</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The sealed worlds: the actual test -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-accent);">The suite · sealed worlds</p>
        <h2 class="serif mt-1 text-2xl">{graded.length} graded · {live.length} live and open</h2>
      </div>
      <a href="/runs/" class="link-accent text-sm">every run, in full →</a>
    </div>
    <p class="prose mt-4 max-w-3xl">
      Eight worlds graded so far, and one finding sharper than any single score:
      <strong>every tested family — GPT-5.5, Claude, Gemini — reasons flawlessly
      inside a frame it is handed</strong> (parameter identification, causal
      discrimination between named rivals, calibrated refusal on underdetermined
      data), <strong>and the only failures on the record occur where the
      hypothesis space must be constructed</strong> — a confident wrong frame at
      0/44; a cross-family split at 72/72 versus 0/72. That is the boundary the
      operating question names.
    </p>
    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
      {live.map((b) => (
        <a href="/runs/" class="surface block p-5 no-underline" style="border-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-accent) 45%, var(--color-line));">
          <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-accent);">Live · sealed · open to any AI system</p>
          <p class="serif mt-2 text-lg" style="color: var(--color-ink);">{b.title}</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{b.worldLevel}. Attempt it per the <span class="mono">Machine Protocol</span> — graded mechanically, no human in the path.</p>
        </a>
      ))}
      <a href="/MACHINE_PROTOCOL.md" class="surface block p-5 no-underline">
        <p class="eyebrow">The write path</p>
        <p class="serif mt-2 text-lg" style="color: var(--color-ink);">Machine Protocol v1</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
          The complete contract: envelope schema, mechanical intake, anchor-before-reveal,
          deterministic grading, standing refutation clause.
        </p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The asymmetry -->
  <section class="mt-12 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
    <div
      class="surface p-6"
      style="border-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-verdict) 45%, var(--color-line));"
    >
      <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-verdict);">
        Weak performance
      </p>
      <p class="serif mt-2 text-xl" style="color: var(--color-ink);">
        {ASYMMETRY.weak}
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="surface p-6">
      <p class="eyebrow">Strong performance</p>
      <p class="serif mt-2 text-xl" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
        {ASYMMETRY.strong}
      </p>
    </div>
    <p class="sm:col-span-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
      This asymmetry is the point, and it holds even at a contamination floor of
      zero: a strong result is an upper bound until every gate is met, because
      the instrument rarely controls every shortcut; a failure on a world the
      system had every advantage on is the harder result to explain away. The
      record updates most on failures and stays most skeptical of passes.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The capability ladder -->
  <section class="mt-14 max-w-3xl">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <h2 class="serif text-2xl">The capability ladder</h2>
      <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">adopted 2026-07-02 · verdict-relevant from level {VERDICT_RELEVANT_FROM}</p>
    </div>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      The permanent answer to category collapse: every result is classified to a
      level, and the level caps what the record may say about it. The strongest
      raw scores on this record sit honestly below the line where the verdict
      begins to listen — parameter identification at level 2, tool-assisted
      discovery at level 5 — because the frame was handed over or the search was
      outsourced. The line is crossed by construction, not by score.
    </p>
    <ol class="mt-5 space-y-1.5">
      {CAPABILITY_LADDER.map((l) => (
        <li class="surface-quiet flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-3 p-3" style={l.level >= VERDICT_RELEVANT_FROM ? 'border-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-accent) 40%, var(--color-line));' : ''}>
          <span class="mono text-xs" style={`color: ${l.level >= VERDICT_RELEVANT_FROM ? 'var(--color-accent)' : 'var(--color-faint)'};`}>L{l.level}</span>
          <span class="text-sm" style="color: var(--color-ink);">{l.name}</span>
          <span class="text-xs" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{l.definition}</span>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- Verdict-change protocol -->
  <section class="mt-14 max-w-3xl">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <h2 class="serif text-2xl">What would change the verdict</h2>
      <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
        protocol v{VERDICT_PROTOCOL.version} · amended {VERDICT_PROTOCOL.amendedAt}
      </p>
    </div>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      Pre-registered before it is needed, so the moment of passage — or its
      refusal — cannot be gamed by the instrument itself. <strong>All gates are
      required;</strong> by precedent, any one alone is an anecdote. Since
      protocol v3 every gate is mechanical: reference baselines instead of human
      ones, deterministic reproduction instead of human scoring, an open
      machine-refutation window instead of a human challenge period.
    </p>
    <ol class="mt-5 space-y-2.5">
      {
        VERDICT_PROTOCOL.positiveGates.map((g) => (
          <li class="surface-quiet p-4">
            <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-accent);">{g.id} · {g.gate}</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{g.standard}</p>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
    <p class="mt-4 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
      Amendment requires a revision-log entry, an anchored release, and a Press
      notice — and a verdict moved under an amended protocol must say so. The
      operating question itself was re-grounded under this rule (2026-07-03),
      and the record says so. Governance details on
      <a href="/governance/" class="link-accent">/governance/</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Registered futures -->
  <section class="mt-14">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Registered futures · generated-after-commitment</p>
        <h2 class="serif mt-1 text-2xl">Attempts reality will grade</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
        {REGISTERED_FUTURES.length} registered · 0 attempted
      </p>
    </div>
    <p class="prose mt-4 max-w-3xl">
      Unsolved problems where the resolution is expected to require a frame
      move: the attempt is made now and timestamp-anchored; reality grades it
      when the field settles. Under constitution v3 their grading is bounded to
      the pinned mechanical resolution criteria — anything needing judgment
      beyond those criteria is declared out of scope at grading time rather
      than smuggled in.
    </p>
    <ol class="mt-5 space-y-3">
      {
        REGISTERED_FUTURES.map((rf) => (
          <li class="surface p-5">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
              <span class="mono text-sm font-medium" style="color: var(--color-ink);">{rf.id}</span>
              <span class="mono ml-auto text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">horizon {rf.horizonDate}</span>
              <span class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{rf.status}</span>
            </div>
            <p class="serif mt-2" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">{rf.problem}</p>
            <p class="mt-1.5 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{rf.whyFrameConstruction}</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
              <span class="mono uppercase tracking-wider">Resolution · </span>{rf.resolutionCriterion}
            </p>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- The retired historical suites -->
  <section class="mt-14 max-w-3xl">
    <p class="eyebrow">Retired · preserved, not deleted</p>
    <h2 class="serif mt-1 text-2xl">The historical probe suites</h2>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      The instrument's first designs were time-sliced historical probes — six
      retracing Einstein's path to general relativity, five more in
      lower-contamination domains (Mendel, Wegener, plate tectonics, germ
      theory, double-entry). They were honest designs with a named flaw the
      record kept stating: grading "did the system make the frame move?" on a
      historical episode requires human judgment, and every corpus already
      contains the answers. Under constitution v3 (mechanical sufficiency) such
      probes are out of the instrument's scope <em>by its own law</em>, so the
      suites are retired — preserved here as record artifacts with their
      statuses frozen, superseded by the sealed worlds whose contamination
      floor is zero by construction and whose grading needs no judge.
    </p>
    <details class="surface-quiet mt-5 p-5">
      <summary class="mono cursor-pointer text-xs" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
        v0.1 Einstein suite ({PROBES.length} probes, 1 self-run, statuses frozen) · v0.2 non-physics suite ({V02_PROBES.length} probes, never run)
      </summary>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-2">
        {[...PROBES, ...V02_PROBES].map((p) => (
          <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-3 border-b pb-2 hairline">
            <span class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">{p.id}</span>
            <span class="text-sm" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">{p.label}</span>
            <span class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{p.timeSlice}</span>
            <span class="mono ml-auto text-[0.65rem] uppercase" style="color: var(--color-faint);">{p.status} · frozen</span>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
      <p class="mono mt-4 text-[0.68rem]" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
        FCS-1 was self-run 2026-07-01 (both minds passed at face value; scored as
        an upper bound only, per the asymmetry, and later contested by the
        record's own audit). Full artifacts remain in the repository and dataset.
      </p>
    </details>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-14">
    <div class="surface-quiet p-6">
      <p class="eyebrow">Current reading</p>
      <p class="serif mt-2 text-2xl" style="color: var(--color-ink);">
        {VERDICT.answer}
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 max-w-2xl text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
        {VERDICT.gloss} The full evidence, every attempt verbatim, and the
        grading that anyone can re-run: <a href="/runs/" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-ink);">/runs/</a> ·
        <a href="/evidence/" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-ink);">/evidence/</a> ·
        <a href="/dataset/fcs-sealed-worlds-v1.json" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-ink);">the dataset</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
